  <questiontext format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[
<h3>Week 10 &ndash; Q1: Series RLC Natural Response (Switch Opening)</h3>
<p><em>Course: Electromagnetism and Circuit Analysis &mdash; LUT University, Finland</em></p>
<p><em>This is a training exercise &mdash; you may use books, tutors, and AI. The question requires multi-step reasoning.</em></p>
<p><strong>Total: 8 points | Penalty per wrong attempt: 10%</strong></p>

<hr />

<p>A series RLC circuit is powered by a DC voltage source \(V_s = {@Vs_val@}\;\text{V}\).
The circuit contains a resistor \(R = {@R_val@}\;\Omega\), an inductor \(L = {@L_val@}\;\text{H}\),
and a capacitor \(C = {@C_uF@}\;\mu\text{F}\), all connected in series with the source and a switch.</p>

<p>The circuit has been in <strong>steady state for a long time</strong>.
At \(t = 0\), the switch <strong>opens</strong>, disconnecting the DC source and leaving the series RLC loop isolated.</p>

<p>Your task: determine the complete natural response \(i(t)\) for \(t &gt; 0\) by working through parts (a)&ndash;(f) below.</p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (a) &mdash; DC Steady-State Concept (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Before the switch opens (\(t &lt; 0\)), the circuit has been in DC steady state for a very long time.
Which statement correctly describes the initial conditions?</p>
<ol>
  <li>Capacitor = open circuit at DC &rarr; \(i(0^-) = 0\;\text{A}\), \(v_C(0^-) = V_s\)</li>
  <li>Inductor = open circuit at DC &rarr; \(i(0^-) = 0\), \(v_C(0^-) = 0\)</li>
  <li>Both components block DC &rarr; \(i = 0\), \(v_C = 0\)</li>
  <li>Inductor = short circuit carrying \(V_s/R\) &rarr; \(v_C = 0\)</li>
</ol>
<p>Enter the number of the correct option (1&ndash;4):
[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (b1) &mdash; Initial Current \(i(0^+)\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Using the DC steady-state analysis and continuity conditions, what is \(i(0^+)\) in Amperes?</p>
<p>\(i(0^+) = \) [[input:ans2]] A [[validation:ans2]]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (b2) &mdash; Initial Capacitor Voltage \(v_C(0^+)\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>What is the value of \(v_C(0^+)\) in Volts? (Express to 3 significant figures.)</p>
<p>\(v_C(0^+) = \) [[input:ans3]] V [[validation:ans3]]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (c1) &mdash; Damping Coefficient \(\alpha\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Calculate the damping coefficient \(\alpha\) (in rad/s) for this series RLC circuit.
(Express to 3 significant figures.)</p>
<p>\(\alpha = \) [[input:ans4]] rad/s [[validation:ans4]]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (c2) &mdash; Natural Frequency \(\omega_0\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Calculate the resonant (natural) frequency \(\omega_0\) (in rad/s).
(Express to 3 significant figures.)</p>
<p>\(\omega_0 = \) [[input:ans5]] rad/s [[validation:ans5]]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (d) &mdash; Damping Regime Classification (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Based on your values of \(\alpha\) and \(\omega_0\), classify the damping regime:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Overdamped (\(\alpha &gt; \omega_0\))</li>
  <li>Underdamped (\(\alpha &lt; \omega_0\))</li>
  <li>Critically damped (\(\alpha = \omega_0\))</li>
</ol>
<p>Enter the number of the correct regime (1&ndash;3):
[[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (e) &mdash; Characteristic Root \(s_1\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Find the characteristic root \(s_1\) with the <strong>larger real part</strong>
(or positive imaginary part if complex conjugate pair).</p>
<p><em>Syntax hint: For complex roots use <code>j</code> for the imaginary unit,
e.g., <code>-2800+9600*j</code></em></p>
<p>\(s_1 = \) [[input:ans7]] [[validation:ans7]]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Part (f) &mdash; Complete Current Response \(i(t)\) (1 pt)</h4>
<p>Write the complete expression for \(i(t)\) (in Amperes) for \(t &gt; 0\).</p>
<p><em>Syntax hint: Use <code>exp(...)</code>, <code>sin(...)</code>, <code>cos(...)</code>,
and <code>t</code> as the time variable.<br />
Example: <code>-0.104*exp(-2800*t)*sin(9600*t)</code></em></p>
<p>\(i(t) = \) [[input:ans8]] A [[validation:ans8]]</p>
]]></text>
  </questiontext>

  <generalfeedback format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[
<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<h4>Step 1: DC Steady-State Analysis</h4>
<p>After a very long time in DC steady state:</p>
<ul>
  <li>The <strong>capacitor</strong> acts as an <strong>open circuit</strong> (it blocks DC current after fully charging).</li>
  <li>The <strong>inductor</strong> acts as a <strong>short circuit</strong> (zero voltage drop across it at constant current).</li>
</ul>
<p>Since the capacitor is open, no current flows in the series loop:</p>
<p>\[i(0^-) = 0\;\text{A}\]</p>
<p>With no current flowing, there is no voltage drop across \(R\) or \(L\).
All the source voltage appears across the capacitor:</p>
<p>\[v_C(0^-) = V_s = {@Vs_val@}\;\text{V}\]</p>
<p>By continuity of inductor current and capacitor voltage:</p>
<p>\[i(0^+) = i(0^-) = 0\;\text{A}, \quad v_C(0^+) = v_C(0^-) = {@ta3@}\;\text{V}\]</p>

<h4>Step 2: Damping Parameters</h4>
<p>For a <strong>series</strong> RLC circuit:</p>
<p>\[\alpha = \frac{R}{2L} = \frac{{@R_val@}}{2 \times {@L_val@}} = {@ta_alpha@}\;\text{rad/s}\]</p>
<p>\[\omega_0 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{LC}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{{@L_val@} \times {@C_val@}}} = {@ta_omega0@}\;\text{rad/s}\]</p>

<h4>Step 3: Damping Regime Classification</h4>
<p>Comparing \(\alpha = {@ta_alpha@}\;\text{rad/s}\) with \(\omega_0 = {@ta_omega0@}\;\text{rad/s}\):</p>
<p>The circuit is <strong>{@regime_name@}</strong>.</p>

<h4>Step 4: Initial Derivative</h4>
<p>After the switch opens, KVL around the isolated series RLC loop gives:</p>
<p>\[L\frac{di}{dt} + Ri + v_C = 0\]</p>
<p>At \(t = 0^+\):</p>
<p>\[\frac{di}{dt}(0^+) = \frac{1}{L}\left(-R \cdot i(0^+) - v_C(0^+)\right)
= \frac{1}{{@L_val@}}\left(-{@R_val@} \cdot 0 - {@Vs_val@}\right)
= {@didt0@}\;\text{A/s}\]</p>

<h4>Step 5: Complete Response</h4>
<p>Applying the initial conditions \(i(0) = 0\) and \(\frac{di}{dt}(0) = {@didt0@}\;\text{A/s}\):</p>
<p>\[i(t) = {@ta8@}\;\text{A}, \quad t &gt; 0\]</p>

<hr />

<h4>Answer Summary</h4>
<table border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0">
  <tr><th>Part</th><th>Quantity</th><th>Correct Answer</th></tr>
  <tr><td>(a)</td><td>DC steady-state concept</td><td>Option {@ta1@}</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(b1)</td><td>\(i(0^+)\)</td><td>{@ta2@} A</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(b2)</td><td>\(v_C(0^+)\)</td><td>{@ta3@} V</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(c1)</td><td>\(\alpha\)</td><td>{@ta4@} rad/s</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(c2)</td><td>\(\omega_0\)</td><td>{@ta5@} rad/s</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(d)</td><td>Damping regime</td><td>{@regime_name@} (option {@ta6@})</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(e)</td><td>\(s_1\)</td><td>{@ta7@}</td></tr>
  <tr><td>(f)</td><td>\(i(t)\)</td><td>{@ta8@} A</td></tr>
</table>
]]></text>
